gland, United Kingdom","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","England":"England","Northampton, Northampton Borough, Northamptonshire, England":"Northampton, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","East Riding, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bocland","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Boland   1 and 2.","English: variant of   Bolland   2.","Americanized form of German <b>Bauland</b>: topographic name for someone who lived by land that was under cultivation."],"variants":[{"name":"Boland","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aidan, Bridie, Caitlin, Donal, Finbar, Maeve.","English: habitational name from the district of Bowland (Forest) in North Yorkshire and Lancashire. Robert <i>of Bowland</i> was a member of the garrison of Stirling castle in Scotland in 1339–40, and was presumably a Yorkshireman or a Lancastrian.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Beólláin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Beóllán</i>’, an old Irish name of uncertain origin. See   Bolan   1."]}]},{"name":"Juliana","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["feminine form of <i>Julianus</i> (  see  Julian  ), which was revived in England in the 18th century and has been used occasionally ever since."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":1,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":14,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":23,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Juliana de Bocland was born in 1314, in Warminster, Wiltshire, England, her father, Ralph de Bocland, was 28 and her mother, Katherine de Warwick, was 18. She married Sir John de Mauduit of Warminster in 1327, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died on 20 April 1379, in Warminster, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 65, and was buried in Northampton, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1314–20 April 1379":"1314–20. aprill 1379","1314–1379":"1314–1379","1310–1348":"1310–1348","1334–1364":"1334–1364","1286–Male":"1286–Surnud","1296–1314":"1296–1314","21 August 1348":"21. august 1348","1286":"1286","1296":"1296","20 April 1379":"20. aprill 1379","1 April 1364":"1. aprill 1364","1327":"1327","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1348":"1348","1314":"1314","1379":"13